webpackJsonp([0x8ebf44bc411b],{507:function(t,e){t.exports={data:{wordpressWpLessons:{id:"19f81973-e840-5630-8c51-c4083a394b51",wordpress_id:6561,title:"Activity: Building HTML Basics",slug:"activity-building-html-basics",content:'<h2>Objectives and Overview</h2>\n<p>The core objective of this activity is to practice building a page with basic HTML elements. You&#8217;ll be using Thimble for this lesson. If you haven&#8217;t made an account yet you should work through <a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/lesson/introducing-thimble/">Introducing Thimble</a> first.</p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll be able to add to this project as your HTML skills develop throughout the module. Try to focus on understanding the purpose of each HTML element that you include.</p>\n<h3>Lesson Objectives:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Use Thimble to practice building a webpage that includes basic HTML elements</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2>Getting Ready</h2>\n<p>The first step is to open a new project in Thimble. The previous lesson outlined the steps for this, so go ahead and keep that lesson in a separate tab if you need a refresher.</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve started a new project, name it something such as &#8220;About Me &#8211; v1&#8221; and then click the <strong>Save</strong> button:</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-6564" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-1024x597.jpg" alt="thimble starter project with new name and save highlighted" width="625" height="364" srcset="https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-1024x597.jpg 1024w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-300x175.jpg 300w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-768x448.jpg 768w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-171x100.jpg 171w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-624x364.jpg 624w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-100x58.jpg 100w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-about-1-750x437.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>At this point, your project should match the above image except for your title. Let&#8217;s take a look at some key elements:</p>\n<h3>Head Section</h3>\n<p>The content contained inside the <strong>&lt;head&gt; &lt;/head&gt;</strong> tags is important information that doesn&#8217;t show up in the preview tab. The <strong>&lt;title&gt; &lt;/title&gt;</strong> is displays in the browser tab.</p>\n<p>One other key element in this section is the <strong>&lt;link&gt;</strong> to the stylesheet. This is important and it connects your CSS stylesheet to the HTML document. You&#8217;ll dive deeper into this in the next group of lessons. For now, you&#8217;re going to focus mainly on the HTML. Just remember that this link is what establishes the connection between your HTML document and your stylesheet.</p>\n<h3>Body Section</h3>\n<p>The elements and content inside the <strong>&lt;body&gt; &lt;/body&gt;</strong> tags make up the display of your page. This is what is displayed in the <em>preview</em> tab in Thimble. Notice that there is an <strong>&lt;h1&gt;</strong> element. This is your top level heading and you typically only want one of these per page. If you change the content in between the <strong>&lt;h1&gt; &lt;/h1&gt;</strong> tags you&#8217;ll see that it changes in the preview:<br />\n<a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-6565" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-1024x458.jpg" alt="thimble editor and preview h1 highlighted" width="625" height="280" srcset="https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-1024x458.jpg 1024w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-300x134.jpg 300w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-768x343.jpg 768w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-200x89.jpg 200w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-624x279.jpg 624w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-100x45.jpg 100w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-h1-750x335.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>The words displayed in the heading are the text contained between the opening and closing <strong>&lt;h1&gt;</strong> tags!</p>\n<p>The next tag, <strong>&lt;p&gt;</strong> is the <em>paragraph</em> element. The text contained between the opening <strong>&lt;p&gt;</strong> tag and the closing <strong>&lt;/p&gt;</strong> is  the paragraph text. Note also that there is text contained with <strong>&lt;strong&gt;</strong> <strong>&lt;/strong</strong><strong>&gt;</strong> tags. Any text contained in those tags becomes <strong>bold</strong>. Take a look at this image:<br />\n<a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-6566" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-1024x455.jpg" alt="thimble editor and preview p highlighted" width="625" height="278" srcset="https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-1024x455.jpg 1024w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-300x133.jpg 300w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-768x341.jpg 768w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-200x89.jpg 200w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-624x277.jpg 624w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-100x44.jpg 100w, https://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-thimble-p-tag-750x333.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>Note that Thimble provides a visual cue in the preview. There is a slight blue box around the content that you&#8217;re currently changing in the editor! This is a helpful guide as you&#8217;re building your skills!</p>\n<p>Remember, the open <strong>&lt;body</strong><strong>&gt;</strong> tag must be paired with a closing <strong>&lt;/body&gt;</strong> at the close of the section, and then the closing <strong>&lt;/html&gt;</strong> tag is the <em>very last tag</em> in the entire document. Try to start noticing the way that these tags nest within each other!</p>\n<h2 class="learn-activity">Activity: Building With HTML</h2>\n<p>Now that you have a basic understanding of HTML, let&#8217;s get started with building some structure to a page. Thimble handles much of the HTML layout for you, so at this point you can focus on adding content to the <strong>body element</strong> that is contained within the opening <strong>&lt;body</strong><strong>&gt;</strong> and closing <strong>&lt;/body&gt;</strong> tags.</p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll start creating an <strong>About Me</strong> page. For now, you&#8217;ll be adding HTML and content only. As you add each of these elements, make sure that you&#8217;re adding things that fit the goal of the project. For example, instead of just listening out random items you should make a list of hobbies or interests.</p>\n<p>For this first activity, you should include the following HTML elements:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>An <strong>&lt;h1&gt;</strong> heading</li>\n<li>Sub-headings, such as <strong>&lt;h2&gt;</strong> and if necessary, <strong>&lt;h3&gt;</strong></li>\n<li>Formatting text inside a <strong>&lt;p&gt;</strong> element. Here are some options:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bold</strong> text inside <strong>&lt;strong</strong><strong>&gt;</strong> tags</li>\n<li><em>Emphasized</em> text inside <strong>&lt;em&gt;</strong> tags</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>An ordered list using the <strong>&lt;ol&gt;</strong> tags</li>\n<li>An unordered list using the <strong>&lt;ul&gt;</strong> tags</li>\n<li>A link using the anchor tags <strong>&lt;a href&gt; &lt;/a&gt;</strong></li>\n<li>An image using the img tags <strong>&lt;img&gt; &lt;/img&gt;</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>It&#8217;s alright if you don&#8217;t finish this all at once! Keep working toward it.</p>\n'}},pathContext:{}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---activity-building-html-basics-ffdb3d69ec86e80c4983.js.map